To investigate the influence of latitudinal contrast in soil moisture on the HWL latitude, we define a soil moisture difference (SMD) index to characterize the meridional contrast in soil moisture across different latitude bands, as follows:4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${SMD}={SM}\left[15^\circ S-15^\circ N\right]-0.5\times ({SM}\left[30^\circ S-15^\circ S\right]+{SM}\left[15^\circ N-30^\circ N\right])$$\end{document}SMD=SM15∘S−15∘N−0.5×(SM30∘S−15∘S+SM15∘N−30∘N)where ‘[]’ denotes the latitude-weighted areal mean. This index reflects the difference in soil moisture between the tropics (15°S–15°N) and subtropics (30°–15°S and 15°–30°N). Additionally, similar result is observed using 20° to separate the tropics and subtropics, confirming the robustness of the SMD definition.
